{"parse":{"title":"Covering cherub","pageid":50030038,"revid":841187661,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p> \n<b>Covering cherub</b> (in literary usage) is the <a href=\"/wiki/Anxiety_of_influence\" title=\"Anxiety of influence\">obstructing presence</a> for the artist of the inherited tradition, and cultural predecessors, with which they are faced.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Origins\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Origins</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Thematics\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Thematics</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Criticism\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Criticism</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origins\">Origins</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Covering_cherub&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Origins\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Found originally in <a href=\"/wiki/Ezekiel\" title=\"Ezekiel\">Ezekiel</a>, the covering cherub was adapted for use by (among others) both <a href=\"/wiki/John_Milton\" title=\"John Milton\">Milton</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/William_Blake\" title=\"William Blake\">William Blake</a>.  In the <a href=\"/wiki/William_Blake%27s_mythology\" title=\"William Blake&#39;s mythology\">Blakean vision</a>, the covering cherub was a composite but always negative figure of truth's guardian turned destructive,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> of a cruel and hardened Selfhood;<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> and it was from Blake that in 1967 <a href=\"/wiki/Harold_Bloom\" title=\"Harold Bloom\">Harold Bloom</a> derived his concept of the covering cherub as a literary/cultural barrier.  Apparently, a waking nightmare he experienced gave rise first to his poem on the subject, \"The Covering Cherub\", and eventually to his book <a href=\"/wiki/Anxiety_of_Influence\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Anxiety of Influence\"><i>The Anxiety of Influence</i></a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Thematics\">Thematics</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Covering_cherub&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Thematics\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>For Bloom, \"the Covering Cherub then is a demon of continuity...cultural history, the dead poets, the embarrassments  of a tradition grown too wealthy to need anything more\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>  Bloom considered the artistic struggle in <a href=\"/wiki/Freud\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Freud\">Freudian</a> terms, as a filial contest with a <a href=\"/wiki/Father_figure\" title=\"Father figure\">father figure</a> carrying cultural authority<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> \u2013 an <a href=\"/wiki/Oedipal_conflict\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Oedipal conflict\">Oedipal conflict</a> with a <a href=\"/wiki/Superego\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Superego\">superego</a> either originally modelled on a cultural hero<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> or influenced subsequently by such an ideal model.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Though initially referencing a patriarchal father/son interaction, the concept of the covering cherub has also been applied to works by women writers such as <a href=\"/wiki/Angela_Carter\" title=\"Angela Carter\">Angela Carter</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> and <a href=\"/wiki/Virginia_Woolf\" title=\"Virginia Woolf\">Virginia Woolf</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Criticism\">Criticism</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Covering_cherub&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Criticism\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Critics have seen Bloom's central image as too open-ended to serve as analyical tool, a vague series of analogies only tenuously working as Bloom desired.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Covering_cherub&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"div-col columns column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 22em; -webkit-column-width: 22em; column-width: 22em;\">\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Sandra_Gilbert#&quot;The_Anxiety_of_Authorship&quot;\" title=\"Sandra Gilbert\">Anxiety of Authorship</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Artaud\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Artaud\">Artaud</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/High_culture\" title=\"High culture\">High culture</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Northrop_Frye\" title=\"Northrop Frye\">Northrop Frye</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Tharmas\" title=\"Tharmas\">Tharmas</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Wallace_Stevens\" title=\"Wallace Stevens\">Wallace Stevens</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Western_canon\" title=\"Western canon\">Western canon</a></li></ul></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Covering_cherub&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">D. Erdman, <i>The Complete Poetry and Prose of William Blake</i> (2008) p. 944 and p. 926</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">N.Marsh, <i>William Blake: The Poems</i> (2012) p. 36</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://hilobrow.com/2013/07/11/harold-bloom/\">Harold Bloom</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">H. Bloom, <i>The Anxiety of Influence</i> (1973) p. 39 and p. 21</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">J. Childers ed., <i>The Columbia Dictionary of Modern Literary and Cultural Criticism</i> (1995) p. 14</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">L. Hudson/B. Jarot, <i>The Way Men Think</i> (1993) p. 44</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">S. Freud, <i>New Introductory Lectures on Psychoanalysis</i> (PFL 2) p. 96</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>Bluebeard Gothic</i> (2012)</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">M. Keane, <i>John Milton's Paradise Lost</i> (2013) p. 75</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-10\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-10\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">J. Doane, <i>Nostalgia and Sexual Difference</i> (2013) p. 90-1</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Covering_cherub&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://newabstraction.net/2012/02/16/angelus-novus/\">Angelus novus</a></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by 